    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/cou2/use-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Use error in the context of ASME V&V 40 refers to errors introduced by the end-user during clinical or operational deployment of the device, not errors in the simulation workflow itself. For this COU, the computational model is used exclusively as a pre-market design-evaluation tool by trained simulation engineers operating under a formal simulation governance plan (SGP-CFD-VAD-003). The SGP specifies mandatory peer-review of all simulation setups, automated boundary-condition checks, and locked solver settings for regulated submissions. Because the model is never deployed directly by clinical end-users and all analyst interactions are governed by procedural controls that are assessed separately under the software QA factor, the residual use-error contribution attributable to simulation-workflow misapplication is below the threshold of materiality for this MRL-5 assessment. Scoping this factor out is consistent with the ASME V&V 40 guidance that permits exclusion when the factor is demonstrably controlled by an alternative assurance mechanism that is itself assessed."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/cou2/equivalency-input-parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Equivalency of input parameters assesses whether the input conditions applied in the validation experiments are sufficiently equivalent to those that will exist in the intended COU to permit credible extrapolation of validation evidence. In this assessment, the validation experiments are conducted on the identical FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry under operating conditions that fully span the COU envelope (as documented under the Relevance of Validation Activities factor, which is assessed at Gradation 3). Because the geometry is identical — not analogous — and the operating envelope is fully bracketed rather than extrapolated, there is no distinct equivalency gap to assess: the validation evidence is directly applicable to the COU without any geometric or parametric mapping. Assessing this factor separately would be redundant with the Relevance of Validation Activities assessment and would not add independent credibility information. Scoping this factor out is therefore appropriate and is consistent with the ASME V&V 40 principle that factors should be assessed only where they represent a distinct and non-redundant source of credibility evidence."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/decision/cou2-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/morrison/actor/credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "All eleven in-scope credibility factors have been assessed and each achieves a level meeting or exceeding the required level for MRL 5. Two factors (Use error and Equivalency of input parameters) are scoped out with documented rationale: use error is controlled by the simulation governance plan assessed under software QA, and equivalency of input parameters is subsumed by the directly applicable validation evidence documented under relevance of validation activities. Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification (N = 1000) confirms that the 95th-percentile NIH prediction remains below the clinical threshold at all five operating points. Mesh GCI values are below 2%, iterative convergence is demonstrated, and output comparison shows prediction errors of 4%–21% — all within the 25% acceptance band. The provenance chain is complete from foundational experimental data through validation results to the credibility claim. No credibility gaps remain among assessed factors. The package is accepted for regulatory submission.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
